recipe.label: Dinner Tonight: Korean Fried Chicken Recipe
instructionLines: Remove the tip of each chicken wing and cut in half at the joint to create 2 pieces.
In a heavy pot such as a dutch oven, pour in canola oil to a depth of 2 inches.
Heat over medium-high until a deep-fry thermometer reads 350¬∞F.

In the meantime, pulse the ginger and garlic in a food processor until minced, then add the soy, gojujang, vinegar, oil, and honey. (You might start with half the gojujang and then add it to taste; different brands have varying levels of spiciness).
In a large bowl, whisk the cornstarch, flour, and water together to make a loose paste.
Add the chicken wings and toss well to coat.
Fry the chicken in batches for 6 minutes, until golden, then drain on paper towels and bring the oil back up to 350¬∞F.
Fry for a second time until it is crisp, 6 to 8 minutes more.
Drain on paper towels, toss with the sauce, and serve.

recipe.label: Seriously Asian: Korean Kabocha Porridge Recipe
ingredientLines: 8 ounces kabocha, seeded, skinned, and cut into 1-inch chunks
chopped walnuts and raisins, to garnish

ingredients.text: 8 ounces kabocha, seeded, skinned, and cut into 1-inch chunks
chopped walnuts and raisins, to garnish
chopped walnuts and raisins, to garnish

instructionLines: Over high heat, steam the kabocha until tender, about 40 minutes.
Place the kabocha in a blender and add 1/2 or so of water.
Pur√©e, leaving a few chunks of the kaboca intact if desired.
Add more water if necessary to bring it to a thick but smooth consistency.
Place the kabocha pur√©e in a medium-sized pot and add the glutinous rice flour.
Over medium heat, simmer the puree for 10 to 15 minutes until thickened.
Add a pinch of salt, if desired.
Serve with chopped walnuts and raisins.

recipe.label: Grilled Cheese With Kimchi Recipe
ingredientLines: 2 tablespoons butter, cut into three even pieces
2 slices hearty white bread, such as Pepperidge Farm or Arnold
2 slices American, Cheddar, or Jack cheese
1/2 cup kimchi, drained and roughly chopped

ingredients.text: 2 tablespoons butter, cut into three even pieces
2 slices hearty white bread, such as Pepperidge Farm or Arnold
2 slices American, Cheddar, or Jack cheese
1/2 cup kimchi, drained and roughly chopped

instructionLines: Melt one third of butter in a large non-stick skillet over medium heat until foaming subsides.
Add both bread slices and cook, swirling occasionally, until pale golden brown on bottom side, about 2 minutes.
Transfer to a cutting board toasted-side-up.
Place one cheese slice on top of one slice of bread.
Top with kimchi and second cheese slice.
Close sandwich, with both toasted sides facing inwards.
Melt one more piece of butter in the skillet and reduce heat to medium low.
Add sandwich and cook, swirling occasionally, until deep, even golden brown, about 5 minutes.
Remove sandwich using a flexible metal spatula.
Add the remaining butter.
Return sandwich to skillet cooked-side up.
Season with salt.
Cook, swirling occasionally, until second side is deep, even golden brown and cheese is thoroughly melted, about 5 minutes.
Serve immediately.

recipe.label: Dinner Tonight: Korean Japchae (Noodles with Spinach, Carrot, and Beef) Recipe
ingredientLines: 3 ounces fresh shitake mushrooms, stems removed, thinly sliced
3 scallions, ends trimmed, cut into 1-inch pieces
6 ounces flank steak, very thinly sliced against the grain
1 carrot, peeled, end trimmed, cut into matchsticks

ingredients.text: 3 ounces fresh shitake mushrooms, stems removed, thinly sliced
3 scallions, ends trimmed, cut into 1-inch pieces
6 ounces flank steak, very thinly sliced against the grain
1 carrot, peeled, end trimmed, cut into matchsticks

instructionLines: Combine the soy sauce and brown sugar in a medium-sized bowl.
Set aside.
Bring a large pot of water to a boil over high heat.
Add the noodles and cook for five minutes.
Drain noodles in a colander and then rinse under cold water.
Drain noodles again.
Cut noodles into 8-inch lengths with a pair of kitchen shears, and toss in a large bowl with the sesame oil.
Set aside.
Place a large wok over high heat.
Add the oil, and when smoking, add the onion, garlic, scallion, and the beef.
Stir-fry until beef is just slightly pink in the middle, 30 seconds to one minute.
Add the carrots, spinach, and mushrooms.
Stir-fry until carrots and tender and spinach has wilted, about one minute.
Pour the soy sauce mixture into the wok and add the noodles.
Toss mixture well, and cook until noodles are warmed through, about two minutes.
Divide mixture between four plates, and garnish with a sprinkling of the sesame seeds.

recipe.label: Max and Eli Sussman's Korean-Style Short Ribs
ingredientLines: 1/3 cup tightly packed dark brown sugar
3 tablespoons sriracha sauce, plus more for serving
1 bunch green onions, white and tender green parts only, thinly sliced
Steamed white rice and hoisin sauce, for serving

ingredients.text: 1/3 cup tightly packed dark brown sugar
3 tablespoons sriracha sauce, plus more for serving
1 bunch green onions, white and tender green parts only, thinly sliced
Steamed white rice and hoisin sauce, for serving

instructionLines: In a large bowl, whisk together the soy sauce, 1 cup water, the vinegars, brown sugar, sriracha, and pepper.
Add the yellow onion, green onions, and garlic and stir to blend well.
Add the short ribs and turn to coat well with the marinade.
Cover with plastic wrap and let marinate in the refrigerator for at least 12 hours or, preferably, 24 hours.
Line a large, heavy-duty baking sheet with foil.
Remove the ribs from the marinade and shake off the onions and garlic.
Place on the prepared baking sheet and let come to room temperature (this could take up to an hour).
Preheat the broiler.
Broil the ribs until the surface of the meat begins to caramelize, 5 to 7 minutes.
Remove from the broiler, turn, slide back under the broiler, and broil until cooked through, about 5 minutes longer.
Remove from the broiler and serve right away with rice, hoisin sauce, and additional sriracha.

ingredientLines: 8 ounces tofu, chopped into 1/2 inch pieces
1 tablespoon Korean red pepper paste (go chu jang)

recipe.label: Soondubu Jjigae (Korean Soft Tofu Stew) Recipe
ingredientLines: 1 four-inch-square piece kombu (sea kelp, see note above)
1/2 cup small dried anchovies (optional, see note above)
2 cups very fermented kimchi with juice (see note above)
1/2 pound thinly sliced pork belly or bacon (optional)
6 scallions, finely sliced, greens and whites reserved separately
4 cloves garlic, grated on a microplane grater
2 to 4 tablespoons kochukaru, to taste (Korean dried chili flakes, see note above)
24 ounces soft silken tofu, roughly broken

ingredients.text: 1 four-inch-square piece kombu (sea kelp, see note above)
1/2 cup small dried anchovies (optional, see note above)
2 cups very fermented kimchi with juice (see note above)
1/2 pound thinly sliced pork belly or bacon (optional)
6 scallions, finely sliced, greens and whites reserved separately
4 cloves garlic, grated on a microplane grater
2 to 4 tablespoons kochukaru, to taste (Korean dried chili flakes, see note above)
24 ounces soft silken tofu, roughly broken

instructionLines: Combine kombu and anchovies (if using) and cover with 1 quart water.
Bring to a simmer and remove from heat.
Let stand 5 minutes, then strain.
Discard solids and reserve broth.
Meanwhile, drain kimchi in a fine mesh strainer set over a small bowl, squeezing to remove as much liquid as possible.
Roughly chop kimchi and reserve kimchi and juice separately.
Heat oil in a 2 to 3 quart stone dolsot or saucepan over medium-high heat until shimmering.
Add pork belly and cook, stirring constantly, until just cooked through, about 1 minute.
Add scallion whites, garlic, and chopped kimchi.
Cook, stirring constantly, until fragrant, about 1 minute.
Add kimchi juice, gochujang, and soy sauce.
Cook until vegetables are well-coated in even layer of sauce.
Add strained broth, kochukaru, and soft.
Stir gently and heat until boiling.
Season to taste with more kochukaru or soy sauce if desired.
Remove from heat and add eggs. sprinkle with scallion greens.
Serve immediately while still boiling, gently stirring eggs into the broth.

recipe.label: Dinner Tonight: Korean Roasted Fish Recipe
ingredientLines: 2 pounds fish (like mackerel or trout), scaled and gutted

ingredients.text: 2 pounds fish (like mackerel or trout), scaled and gutted

instructionLines: Preheat the oven to 375¬∞F.
Rinse fish under cold water, and then dry with some paper towels.
Sprinkle a bit of canola oil on a baking sheet, and set the fish on top.
Make four diagonal slashes on each side of the fish.
Sprinkle the salt on the fish.
Place baking sheet in the oven and cook for about 8 minutes.
Meanwhile, whisk together the rest of the ingredients for the sauce.
Remove the baking sheet with the fish and turn the oven to 425 degrees.
Brush the sauce on to both sides of the fish.
Return the fish to the oven, and cook for about 3 minutes.
Remove the baking sheet with the fish.
Turn on the broiler.
Slide the fish under the broiler and cook for about 1 minute for each side.
The skin should get crisp and slightly blacken.

recipe.label: Ssamjang (Korean Barbecue Dipping Sauce) Recipe
instructionLines: In a small bowl, stir together doenjang, gochujang, rice syrup, sesame oil, scallions, garlic, and sesame seeds until well-combined.
Serve, or transfer to an airtight container and refrigerate until ready to use.

recipe.label: DIY Spicy Kimchi Beef Instant Noodles Recipe
ingredientLines: 4 tablespoons high quality beef base such as Better Than Bouilllon
4 tablespoons chili-garlic sauce (more or less to taste)
1 cup thinly sliced shiitake mushroom caps
4 ounces beef jerky, cut into 1/2-inch squares
4 small nests rice noodles or pre-cooked ramen or Italian pasta (see note above)

ingredients.text: 4 tablespoons high quality beef base such as Better Than Bouilllon
4 tablespoons chili-garlic sauce (more or less to taste)
1 cup thinly sliced shiitake mushroom caps
4 ounces beef jerky, cut into 1/2-inch squares
4 small nests rice noodles or pre-cooked ramen or Italian pasta (see note above)

instructionLines: Divide beef base, kimchi, chili-garlic sauce, mushrooms, beef, and noodles between 4 resealable glass jars.
Divide scallions between 4 small zipper-lock bags and seal bags, squeezing out all of the air.
Tuck bags into jars and seal.
Refrigerate for up to 4 days.
When ready to serve, remove scallion packet and add boiling water to the top of the jar.
Seal jar and let sit 2 minutes.
Open jar, stir in scallions, and serve.

recipe.label: Rice Cakes with Kimchi, Bacon, and Spinach Recipe
ingredientLines: 1 pound Korean rice cakes, cut into 2-inch lengths
10 ounces spinach, cleaned, stemmed, and chopped

ingredients.text: 1 pound Korean rice cakes, cut into 2-inch lengths
10 ounces spinach, cleaned, stemmed, and chopped

instructionLines: Cook bacon in a large 12-inch skillet set over medium heat until fat has rendered and bacon is crispy, about 6 minutes.
When done, remove bacon pieces with a slotted spoon, leaving as much of the fat behind as possible.
Drain bacon on paper towels.
Increase heat to medium-high.
When fat starts to smoke, add as many of the rice cakes as will fit in one layer, approximately half.
Cook undisturbed until crusty on the bottom, about 20 seconds, and then flip the pieces with a spatula.
Cook until crusty on this side, another 20 seconds.
Remove the pieces with a slotted spoon and drain on paper towels.
Repeat process until all the rice cakes are cooked.
When done, turn the heat off.
Discard all but one tablespoon of the fat, and heat over medium heat until shimmering.
Add half of the spinach, and cook, tossing occasionally with a pair of tongs, until wilted.
Add in the other half, and cook until wilted.
Add the kimchi, and cook until any liquid has evaporated.
In a small bowl, whisk together the rice vinegar and the sugar.
Pour this into the skillet, along with the cooked rice cakes.
Toss until everything is mixed together and warm.
Serve immediately with a sprinkling of scallions and sesame seeds.

recipe.label: Caramelized Kimchi Relish
instructionLines: Heat large skillet until very hot.
In a bowl, toss half of the kimchi with the sugar and vinegar and add it to the skillet.
Cook over high heat until the liquid is thickened and sticky and the kimchi is browned in spots, 5 to 6 minutes.
Let cool slightly.
Scrape the caramelized kimchi back into to the bowl.
Add the uncooked kimchi, then toss and serve.

recipe.label: Korean Dates Tea
ingredientLines: 1 piece ginger. Bigger the piece more ginger taste. Cut ginger into chunks

ingredients.text: 1 piece ginger. Bigger the piece more ginger taste. Cut ginger into chunks

instructionLines: In a large pot, fill the water almost to the top.
Boil all ingredients together in a pot of water for about 3 hours.
Drain all ingredients so that all you have left is the liquid.
Enjoy!
You may add honey to taste.
Keep rest in refrigerator and it can keep for 2 weeks.

recipe.label: KOREAN CORN TEA (OKSUSU CHA)
instructionLines: Roast the corn kernels in a dry pan over medium heat.
Move them around often until they darken and are almost blackened in parts, about 10 - 15 minutes. (You can roast more corn and store in an air-tight container for later use).
Transfer the roasted corn to a pot and top with 6 cups of water.
Bring to the boil, and then simmer for 20 minutes.
Taste the tea at this stage and add more water if you feel it‚Äôs too strong, or more corn if you‚Äôd like to elevate the flavour.
Strain the corn kernels and serve hot.
Alternatively, refrigerate and serve chilled.

recipe.label: Icy-Cold Korean Cucumber Soup (Oi Naengguk) Recipe
ingredientLines: One 1-pound (500g) cucumber, preferably Korean or English (about 8 to 10 inches/20 to 25cm long; see note)
2 tablespoons (30ml) Joseon ganjang (Korean soup soy sauce; see note)
2 tablespoons (30ml) Korean yangjo vinegar (brown rice vinegar; see note)
18 ounces ice cubes (500g; the equivalent of 2 1/4 cups/500ml water frozen into cubes)

ingredients.text: One 1-pound (500g) cucumber, preferably Korean or English (about 8 to 10 inches/20 to 25cm long; see note)
2 tablespoons (30ml) Joseon ganjang (Korean soup soy sauce; see note)
2 tablespoons (30ml) Korean yangjo vinegar (brown rice vinegar; see note)
18 ounces ice cubes (500g; the equivalent of 2 1/4 cups/500ml water frozen into cubes)

instructionLines: Cut cucumber into roughly 4-inch (10cm) lengths.
Using a knife or mandoline, julienne the cucumber as finely as you can.
In a large mixing bowl, combine cucumber with garlic, water, soy sauce, and vinegar, stirring to distribute ingredients.
Season with salt.
Transfer to refrigerator if not serving right away.
When ready to serve, add ice cubes and season once more with salt, if needed.
Sprinkle sesame seeds on top.
Ladle into individual bowls, along with the ice cubes, and serve.

recipe.label: Spicy Noodles With Peanut Butter & Kimchi
ingredientLines: 1 cup chopped kimchi, divided, brine reserved

ingredients.text: 1 cup chopped kimchi, divided, brine reserved

instructionLines: Cook the noodles in salted boiling water until they‚Äôre toothsome-meets-chewy.
A couple minutes before the box says they‚Äôre ready, start tasting frequently.
While those are in the works, combine the peanut butter and ¬Ω cup kimchi in a food processor, and blend until combined.
Add 3 tablespoons of liquid‚Äîeither a combo of kimchi brine and water (I like half and half), or all kimchi brine, or all water, depending on how much spice and acidity you‚Äôre looking for.
Blend again, scraping down as needed, until smooth-ish.
Taste and add salt if needed, then transfer to a big heatproof bowl.
When the noodles are done, drain them into a colander in the sink and rinse very well with cold water.
Shake a couple times, then add the cold noodles to the sauce.
Toss until coated, then add more kimchi brine or water, if needed, to get the sauce to the consistency you want.
These are best as soon as they‚Äôre tossed, but they also hold well at room temperature for a couple hours.
Or refrigerate for later. (Just keep in mind that the sauce will thicken further in the fridge‚Äîyou can thin with kimchi brine or water as needed.)
Whenever you serve, pile the remaining ¬Ω cup kimchi on top.
